60 /* The md->capture_last field uses the lower 16 bits for the last captured
61 substring (which can never be greater than 65535) and a bit in the top half
62 to mean "capture vector overflowed". This odd way of doing things was
63 implemented when it was realized that preserving and restoring the overflow bit
64 whenever the last capture number was saved/restored made for a neater
65 interface, and doing it this way saved on (a) another variable, which would
66 have increased the stack frame size (a big NO-NO in PCRE) and (b) another
67 separate set of save/restore instructions. The following defines are used in
68 implementing this. */

131 static void
132 pchars(const pcre_uchar *p, int length, BOOL is_subject, match_data *md)
133 {
134 pcre_uint32 c;
135 BOOL utf = md->utf;
136 if (is_subject && length > md->end_subject - p) length = md->end_subject - p;
137 while (length-- > 0)
138  if (isprint(c = UCHAR21INCTEST(p))) printf("%c", (char)c); else printf("\\x{%02x}", c);
139 }

144 /*************************************************
145 * Match a back-reference *
146 *************************************************/
147 
148 /* Normally, if a back reference hasn't been set, the length that is passed is
149 negative, so the match always fails. However, in JavaScript compatibility mode,
150 the length passed is zero. Note that in caseless UTF-8 mode, the number of
151 subject bytes matched may be different to the number of reference bytes.
152 
153 Arguments:
154  offset index into the offset vector
155  eptr pointer into the subject
156  length length of reference to be matched (number of bytes)
157  md points to match data block
158  caseless TRUE if caseless
159 
160 Returns: >= 0 the number of subject bytes matched
161  -1 no match
162  -2 partial match; always given if at end subject
163 */
164 
165 static int
166 match_ref(int offset, register PCRE_PUCHAR eptr, int length, match_data *md,
167  BOOL caseless)
168 {
169 PCRE_PUCHAR eptr_start = eptr;
170 register PCRE_PUCHAR p = md->start_subject + md->offset_vector[offset];
171 #if defined SUPPORT_UTF && defined SUPPORT_UCP
172 BOOL utf = md->utf;
173 #endif
174 
175 #ifdef PCRE_DEBUG
176 if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
177  printf("matching subject <null>");
178 else
179  {
180  printf("matching subject ");
181  pchars(eptr, length, TRUE, md);
182  }
183 printf(" against backref ");
184 pchars(p, length, FALSE, md);
185 printf("\n");
186 #endif
187 
188 /* Always fail if reference not set (and not JavaScript compatible - in that
189 case the length is passed as zero). */
190 
191 if (length < 0) return -1;
192 
193 /* Separate the caseless case for speed. In UTF-8 mode we can only do this
194 properly if Unicode properties are supported. Otherwise, we can check only
195 ASCII characters. */
196 
197 if (caseless)
198  {
199 #if defined SUPPORT_UTF && defined SUPPORT_UCP
200  if (utf)
201  {
202  /* Match characters up to the end of the reference. NOTE: the number of
203  data units matched may differ, because in UTF-8 there are some characters
204  whose upper and lower case versions code have different numbers of bytes.
205  For example, U+023A (2 bytes in UTF-8) is the upper case version of U+2C65
206  (3 bytes in UTF-8); a sequence of 3 of the former uses 6 bytes, as does a
207  sequence of two of the latter. It is important, therefore, to check the
208  length along the reference, not along the subject (earlier code did this
209  wrong). */
210 
211  PCRE_PUCHAR endptr = p + length;
212  while (p < endptr)
213  {
214  pcre_uint32 c, d;
215  const ucd_record *ur;
216  if (eptr >= md->end_subject) return -2; /* Partial match */
217  GETCHARINC(c, eptr);
218  GETCHARINC(d, p);
219  ur = GET_UCD(d);
220  if (c != d && c != d + ur->other_case)
221  {
222  const pcre_uint32 *pp = PRIV(ucd_caseless_sets) + ur->caseset;
223  for (;;)
224  {
225  if (c < *pp) return -1;
226  if (c == *pp++) break;
227  }
228  }
229  }
230  }
231  else
232 #endif
233 
234  /* The same code works when not in UTF-8 mode and in UTF-8 mode when there
235  is no UCP support. */
236  {
237  while (length-- > 0)
238  {
239  pcre_uint32 cc, cp;
240  if (eptr >= md->end_subject) return -2; /* Partial match */
241  cc = UCHAR21TEST(eptr);
242  cp = UCHAR21TEST(p);
243  if (TABLE_GET(cp, md->lcc, cp) != TABLE_GET(cc, md->lcc, cc)) return -1;
244  p++;
245  eptr++;
246  }
247  }
248  }
249 
250 /* In the caseful case, we can just compare the bytes, whether or not we
251 are in UTF-8 mode. */
252 
253 else
254  {
255  while (length-- > 0)
256  {
257  if (eptr >= md->end_subject) return -2; /* Partial match */
258  if (UCHAR21INCTEST(p) != UCHAR21INCTEST(eptr)) return -1;
259  }
260  }
261 
262 return (int)(eptr - eptr_start);
263 }

267 /***************************************************************************
268 ****************************************************************************
269  RECURSION IN THE match() FUNCTION
270 
271 The match() function is highly recursive, though not every recursive call
272 increases the recursive depth. Nevertheless, some regular expressions can cause
273 it to recurse to a great depth. I was writing for Unix, so I just let it call
274 itself recursively. This uses the stack for saving everything that has to be
275 saved for a recursive call. On Unix, the stack can be large, and this works
276 fine.
277 
278 It turns out that on some non-Unix-like systems there are problems with
279 programs that use a lot of stack. (This despite the fact that every last chip
280 has oodles of memory these days, and techniques for extending the stack have
281 been known for decades.) So....
282 
283 There is a fudge, triggered by defining NO_RECURSE, which avoids recursive
284 calls by keeping local variables that need to be preserved in blocks of memory
285 obtained from malloc() instead instead of on the stack. Macros are used to
286 achieve this so that the actual code doesn't look very different to what it
287 always used to.
288 
289 The original heap-recursive code used longjmp(). However, it seems that this
290 can be very slow on some operating systems. Following a suggestion from Stan
291 Switzer, the use of longjmp() has been abolished, at the cost of having to
292 provide a unique number for each call to RMATCH. There is no way of generating
293 a sequence of numbers at compile time in C. I have given them names, to make
294 them stand out more clearly.
295 
296 Crude tests on x86 Linux show a small speedup of around 5-8%. However, on
297 FreeBSD, avoiding longjmp() more than halves the time taken to run the standard
298 tests. Furthermore, not using longjmp() means that local dynamic variables
299 don't have indeterminate values; this has meant that the frame size can be
300 reduced because the result can be "passed back" by straight setting of the
301 variable instead of being passed in the frame.
302 ****************************************************************************
303 ***************************************************************************/
304 
305 /* Numbers for RMATCH calls. When this list is changed, the code at HEAP_RETURN
306 below must be updated in sync. */

344 /* These versions of the macros manage a private stack on the heap. Note that
345 the "rd" argument of RMATCH isn't actually used in this definition. It's the md
346 argument of match(), which never changes. */
347 
348 #define REGISTER
349 
350 #define RMATCH(ra,rb,rc,rd,re,rw)\
351  {\
352  heapframe *newframe = frame->Xnextframe;\
353  if (newframe == NULL)\
354  {\
355  newframe = (heapframe *)(PUBL(stack_malloc))(sizeof(heapframe));\
356  if (newframe == NULL) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_NOMEMORY);\
357  newframe->Xnextframe = NULL;\
358  frame->Xnextframe = newframe;\
359  }\
360  frame->Xwhere = rw;\
361  newframe->Xeptr = ra;\
362  newframe->Xecode = rb;\
363  newframe->Xmstart = mstart;\
364  newframe->Xoffset_top = rc;\
365  newframe->Xeptrb = re;\
366  newframe->Xrdepth = frame->Xrdepth + 1;\
367  newframe->Xprevframe = frame;\
368  frame = newframe;\
369  DPRINTF(("restarting from line %d\n", __LINE__));\
370  goto HEAP_RECURSE;\
371  L_##rw:\
372  DPRINTF(("jumped back to line %d\n", __LINE__));\
373  }
374 
375 #define RRETURN(ra)\
376  {\
377  heapframe *oldframe = frame;\
378  frame = oldframe->Xprevframe;\
379  if (frame != NULL)\
380  {\
381  rrc = ra;\
382  goto HEAP_RETURN;\
383  }\
384  return ra;\
385  }

467 /* These macros pack up tests that are used for partial matching, and which
468 appear several times in the code. We set the "hit end" flag if the pointer is
469 at the end of the subject and also past the start of the subject (i.e.
470 something has been matched). For hard partial matching, we then return
471 immediately. The second one is used when we already know we are past the end of
472 the subject. */
473 
474 #define CHECK_PARTIAL()\
475  if (md->partial != 0 && eptr >= md->end_subject && \
476  eptr > md->start_used_ptr) \
477  { \
478  md->hitend = TRUE; \
479  if (md->partial > 1) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_PARTIAL); \
480  }
481 
482 #define SCHECK_PARTIAL()\
483  if (md->partial != 0 && eptr > md->start_used_ptr) \
484  { \
485  md->hitend = TRUE; \
486  if (md->partial > 1) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_PARTIAL); \
487  }

666 
667 if (ecode == NULL)
668  {
669  if (rdepth == 0)
670  return match((PCRE_PUCHAR)&rdepth, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, 1);
671  else
672  {
673  int len = (char *)&rdepth - (char *)eptr;
674  return (len > 0)? -len : len;
675  }
676  }
677 #endif /* NO_RECURSE */
678 
679 /* To save space on the stack and in the heap frame, I have doubled up on some
680 of the local variables that are used only in localised parts of the code, but
681 still need to be preserved over recursive calls of match(). These macros define
682 the alternative names that are used. */
683 
684 #define allow_zero cur_is_word
685 #define cbegroup condition
686 #define code_offset codelink
687 #define condassert condition
688 #define matched_once prev_is_word
689 #define foc number
690 #define save_mark data
691 
692 /* These statements are here to stop the compiler complaining about unitialized
693 variables. */
694 
695 #ifdef SUPPORT_UCP
696 prop_value = 0;
697 prop_fail_result = 0;
698 #endif
699 
700 
701 /* This label is used for tail recursion, which is used in a few cases even
702 when NO_RECURSE is not defined, in order to reduce the amount of stack that is
703 used. Thanks to Ian Taylor for noticing this possibility and sending the
704 original patch. */
705 
706 TAIL_RECURSE:
707 
708 /* OK, now we can get on with the real code of the function. Recursive calls
709 are specified by the macro RMATCH and RRETURN is used to return. When
710 NO_RECURSE is *not* defined, these just turn into a recursive call to match()
711 and a "return", respectively (possibly with some debugging if PCRE_DEBUG is
712 defined). However, RMATCH isn't like a function call because it's quite a
713 complicated macro. It has to be used in one particular way. This shouldn't,
714 however, impact performance when true recursion is being used. */
715 
716 #ifdef SUPPORT_UTF
717 utf = md->utf; /* Local copy of the flag */
718 #else
719 utf = FALSE;
720 #endif
721 
722 /* First check that we haven't called match() too many times, or that we
723 haven't exceeded the recursive call limit. */
724 
725 if (md->match_call_count++ >= md->match_limit) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_MATCHLIMIT);
726 if (rdepth >= md->match_limit_recursion) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_RECURSIONLIMIT);
727 
728 /* At the start of a group with an unlimited repeat that may match an empty
729 string, the variable md->match_function_type is set to MATCH_CBEGROUP. It is
730 done this way to save having to use another function argument, which would take
731 up space on the stack. See also MATCH_CONDASSERT below.
732 
733 When MATCH_CBEGROUP is set, add the current subject pointer to the chain of
734 such remembered pointers, to be checked when we hit the closing ket, in order
735 to break infinite loops that match no characters. When match() is called in
736 other circumstances, don't add to the chain. The MATCH_CBEGROUP feature must
737 NOT be used with tail recursion, because the memory block that is used is on
738 the stack, so a new one may be required for each match(). */
739 
740 if (md->match_function_type == MATCH_CBEGROUP)
741  {
742  newptrb.epb_saved_eptr = eptr;
743  newptrb.epb_prev = eptrb;
744  eptrb = &newptrb;
745  md->match_function_type = 0;
746  }
747 
748 /* Now start processing the opcodes. */
749 
750 for (;;)
751  {
752  minimize = possessive = FALSE;
753  op = *ecode;
754 
755  switch(op)
756  {
757  case OP_MARK:
758  md->nomatch_mark = ecode + 2;
759  md->mark = NULL; /* In case previously set by assertion */
760  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode] + ecode[1], offset_top, md,
761  eptrb, RM55);
762  if ((rrc == MATCH_MATCH || rrc == MATCH_ACCEPT) &&
763  md->mark == NULL) md->mark = ecode + 2;
764 
765  /* A return of MATCH_SKIP_ARG means that matching failed at SKIP with an
766  argument, and we must check whether that argument matches this MARK's
767  argument. It is passed back in md->start_match_ptr (an overloading of that
768  variable). If it does match, we reset that variable to the current subject
769  position and return MATCH_SKIP. Otherwise, pass back the return code
770  unaltered. */
771 
772  else if (rrc == MATCH_SKIP_ARG &&
773  STRCMP_UC_UC_TEST(ecode + 2, md->start_match_ptr) == 0)
774  {
775  md->start_match_ptr = eptr;
776  RRETURN(MATCH_SKIP);
777  }
778  RRETURN(rrc);
779 
780  case OP_FAIL:
781  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
782 
783  case OP_COMMIT:
784  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode], offset_top, md,
785  eptrb, RM52);
786  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
787  RRETURN(MATCH_COMMIT);
788 
789  case OP_PRUNE:
790  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode], offset_top, md,
791  eptrb, RM51);
792  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
793  RRETURN(MATCH_PRUNE);
794 
795  case OP_PRUNE_ARG:
796  md->nomatch_mark = ecode + 2;
797  md->mark = NULL; /* In case previously set by assertion */
798  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode] + ecode[1], offset_top, md,
799  eptrb, RM56);
800  if ((rrc == MATCH_MATCH || rrc == MATCH_ACCEPT) &&
801  md->mark == NULL) md->mark = ecode + 2;
802  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
803  RRETURN(MATCH_PRUNE);
804 
805  case OP_SKIP:
806  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode], offset_top, md,
807  eptrb, RM53);
808  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
809  md->start_match_ptr = eptr; /* Pass back current position */
810  RRETURN(MATCH_SKIP);
811 
812  /* Note that, for Perl compatibility, SKIP with an argument does NOT set
813  nomatch_mark. When a pattern match ends with a SKIP_ARG for which there was
814  not a matching mark, we have to re-run the match, ignoring the SKIP_ARG
815  that failed and any that precede it (either they also failed, or were not
816  triggered). To do this, we maintain a count of executed SKIP_ARGs. If a
817  SKIP_ARG gets to top level, the match is re-run with md->ignore_skip_arg
818  set to the count of the one that failed. */
819 
820  case OP_SKIP_ARG:
821  md->skip_arg_count++;
822  if (md->skip_arg_count <= md->ignore_skip_arg)
823  {
824  ecode += PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode] + ecode[1];
825  break;
826  }
827  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode] + ecode[1], offset_top, md,
828  eptrb, RM57);
829  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
830 
831  /* Pass back the current skip name by overloading md->start_match_ptr and
832  returning the special MATCH_SKIP_ARG return code. This will either be
833  caught by a matching MARK, or get to the top, where it causes a rematch
834  with md->ignore_skip_arg set to the value of md->skip_arg_count. */
835 
836  md->start_match_ptr = ecode + 2;
837  RRETURN(MATCH_SKIP_ARG);
838 
839  /* For THEN (and THEN_ARG) we pass back the address of the opcode, so that
840  the branch in which it occurs can be determined. Overload the start of
841  match pointer to do this. */
842 
843  case OP_THEN:
844  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode], offset_top, md,
845  eptrb, RM54);
846  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
847  md->start_match_ptr = ecode;
848  RRETURN(MATCH_THEN);
849 
850  case OP_THEN_ARG:
851  md->nomatch_mark = ecode + 2;
852  md->mark = NULL; /* In case previously set by assertion */
853  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode] + ecode[1], offset_top,
854  md, eptrb, RM58);
855  if ((rrc == MATCH_MATCH || rrc == MATCH_ACCEPT) &&
856  md->mark == NULL) md->mark = ecode + 2;
857  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
858  md->start_match_ptr = ecode;
859  RRETURN(MATCH_THEN);
860 
861  /* Handle an atomic group that does not contain any capturing parentheses.
862  This can be handled like an assertion. Prior to 8.13, all atomic groups
863  were handled this way. In 8.13, the code was changed as below for ONCE, so
864  that backups pass through the group and thereby reset captured values.
865  However, this uses a lot more stack, so in 8.20, atomic groups that do not
866  contain any captures generate OP_ONCE_NC, which can be handled in the old,
867  less stack intensive way.
868 
869  Check the alternative branches in turn - the matching won't pass the KET
870  for this kind of subpattern. If any one branch matches, we carry on as at
871  the end of a normal bracket, leaving the subject pointer, but resetting
872  the start-of-match value in case it was changed by \K. */
873 
874  case OP_ONCE_NC:
875  prev = ecode;
876  saved_eptr = eptr;
877  save_mark = md->mark;
878  do
879  {
880  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + 1 + LINK_SIZE, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM64);
881  if (rrc == MATCH_MATCH) /* Note: _not_ MATCH_ACCEPT */
882  {
883  mstart = md->start_match_ptr;
884  break;
885  }
886  if (rrc == MATCH_THEN)
887  {
888  next = ecode + GET(ecode,1);
889  if (md->start_match_ptr < next &&
890  (*ecode == OP_ALT || *next == OP_ALT))
891  rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
892  }
893 
894  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
895  ecode += GET(ecode,1);
896  md->mark = save_mark;
897  }
898  while (*ecode == OP_ALT);
899 
900  /* If hit the end of the group (which could be repeated), fail */
901 
902  if (*ecode != OP_ONCE_NC && *ecode != OP_ALT) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
903 
904  /* Continue as from after the group, updating the offsets high water
905  mark, since extracts may have been taken. */
906 
907  do ecode += GET(ecode, 1); while (*ecode == OP_ALT);
908 
909  offset_top = md->end_offset_top;
910  eptr = md->end_match_ptr;
911 
912  /* For a non-repeating ket, just continue at this level. This also
913  happens for a repeating ket if no characters were matched in the group.
914  This is the forcible breaking of infinite loops as implemented in Perl
915  5.005. */
916 
917  if (*ecode == OP_KET || eptr == saved_eptr)
918  {
919  ecode += 1+LINK_SIZE;
920  break;
921  }
922 
923  /* The repeating kets try the rest of the pattern or restart from the
924  preceding bracket, in the appropriate order. The second "call" of match()
925  uses tail recursion, to avoid using another stack frame. */
926 
927  if (*ecode == OP_KETRMIN)
928  {
929  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + 1 + LINK_SIZE, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM65);
930  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
931  ecode = prev;
932  goto TAIL_RECURSE;
933  }
934  else /* OP_KETRMAX */
935  {
936  RMATCH(eptr, prev, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM66);
937  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
938  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
939  goto TAIL_RECURSE;
940  }
941  /* Control never gets here */
942 
943  /* Handle a capturing bracket, other than those that are possessive with an
944  unlimited repeat. If there is space in the offset vector, save the current
945  subject position in the working slot at the top of the vector. We mustn't
946  change the current values of the data slot, because they may be set from a
947  previous iteration of this group, and be referred to by a reference inside
948  the group. A failure to match might occur after the group has succeeded,
949  if something later on doesn't match. For this reason, we need to restore
950  the working value and also the values of the final offsets, in case they
951  were set by a previous iteration of the same bracket.
952 
953  If there isn't enough space in the offset vector, treat this as if it were
954  a non-capturing bracket. Don't worry about setting the flag for the error
955  case here; that is handled in the code for KET. */
956 
957  case OP_CBRA:
958  case OP_SCBRA:
959  number = GET2(ecode, 1+LINK_SIZE);
960  offset = number << 1;
961 
962 #ifdef PCRE_DEBUG
963  printf("start bracket %d\n", number);
964  printf("subject=");
965  pchars(eptr, 16, TRUE, md);
966  printf("\n");
967 #endif
968 
969  if (offset < md->offset_max)
970  {
971  save_offset1 = md->offset_vector[offset];
972  save_offset2 = md->offset_vector[offset+1];
973  save_offset3 = md->offset_vector[md->offset_end - number];
974  save_capture_last = md->capture_last;
975  save_mark = md->mark;
976 
977  DPRINTF(("saving %d %d %d\n", save_offset1, save_offset2, save_offset3));
978  md->offset_vector[md->offset_end - number] =
979  (int)(eptr - md->start_subject);
980 
981  for (;;)
982  {
983  if (op >= OP_SBRA) md->match_function_type = MATCH_CBEGROUP;
984  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode], offset_top, md,
985  eptrb, RM1);
986  if (rrc == MATCH_ONCE) break; /* Backing up through an atomic group */
987 
988  /* If we backed up to a THEN, check whether it is within the current
989  branch by comparing the address of the THEN that is passed back with
990  the end of the branch. If it is within the current branch, and the
991  branch is one of two or more alternatives (it either starts or ends
992  with OP_ALT), we have reached the limit of THEN's action, so convert
993  the return code to NOMATCH, which will cause normal backtracking to
994  happen from now on. Otherwise, THEN is passed back to an outer
995  alternative. This implements Perl's treatment of parenthesized groups,
996  where a group not containing | does not affect the current alternative,
997  that is, (X) is NOT the same as (X|(*F)). */
998 
999  if (rrc == MATCH_THEN)
1000  {
1001  next = ecode + GET(ecode,1);
1002  if (md->start_match_ptr < next &&
1003  (*ecode == OP_ALT || *next == OP_ALT))
1004  rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
1005  }
1006 
1007  /* Anything other than NOMATCH is passed back. */
1008 
1009  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
1010  md->capture_last = save_capture_last;
1011  ecode += GET(ecode, 1);
1012  md->mark = save_mark;
1013  if (*ecode != OP_ALT) break;
1014  }
1015 
1016  DPRINTF(("bracket %d failed\n", number));
1017  md->offset_vector[offset] = save_offset1;
1018  md->offset_vector[offset+1] = save_offset2;
1019  md->offset_vector[md->offset_end - number] = save_offset3;
1020 
1021  /* At this point, rrc will be one of MATCH_ONCE or MATCH_NOMATCH. */
1022 
1023  RRETURN(rrc);
1024  }
1025 
1026  /* FALL THROUGH ... Insufficient room for saving captured contents. Treat
1027  as a non-capturing bracket. */
1028 
1029  /* VVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVV */
1030  /* VVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVV */
1031 
1032  DPRINTF(("insufficient capture room: treat as non-capturing\n"));
1033 
1034  /* VVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVV */
1035  /* VVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVV */
1036 
1037  /* Non-capturing or atomic group, except for possessive with unlimited
1038  repeat and ONCE group with no captures. Loop for all the alternatives.
1039 
1040  When we get to the final alternative within the brackets, we used to return
1041  the result of a recursive call to match() whatever happened so it was
1042  possible to reduce stack usage by turning this into a tail recursion,
1043  except in the case of a possibly empty group. However, now that there is
1044  the possiblity of (*THEN) occurring in the final alternative, this
1045  optimization is no longer always possible.
1046 
1047  We can optimize if we know there are no (*THEN)s in the pattern; at present
1048  this is the best that can be done.
1049 
1050  MATCH_ONCE is returned when the end of an atomic group is successfully
1051  reached, but subsequent matching fails. It passes back up the tree (causing
1052  captured values to be reset) until the original atomic group level is
1053  reached. This is tested by comparing md->once_target with the start of the
1054  group. At this point, the return is converted into MATCH_NOMATCH so that
1055  previous backup points can be taken. */
1056 
1057  case OP_ONCE:
1058  case OP_BRA:
1059  case OP_SBRA:
1060  DPRINTF(("start non-capturing bracket\n"));
1061 
1062  for (;;)
1063  {
1064  if (op >= OP_SBRA || op == OP_ONCE)
1065  md->match_function_type = MATCH_CBEGROUP;
1066 
1067  /* If this is not a possibly empty group, and there are no (*THEN)s in
1068  the pattern, and this is the final alternative, optimize as described
1069  above. */
1070 
1071  else if (!md->hasthen && ecode[GET(ecode, 1)] != OP_ALT)
1072  {
1073  ecode += PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode];
1074  goto TAIL_RECURSE;
1075  }
1076 
1077  /* In all other cases, we have to make another call to match(). */
1078 
1079  save_mark = md->mark;
1080  save_capture_last = md->capture_last;
1081  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode], offset_top, md, eptrb,
1082  RM2);
1083 
1084  /* See comment in the code for capturing groups above about handling
1085  THEN. */
1086 
1087  if (rrc == MATCH_THEN)
1088  {
1089  next = ecode + GET(ecode,1);
1090  if (md->start_match_ptr < next &&
1091  (*ecode == OP_ALT || *next == OP_ALT))
1092  rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
1093  }
1094 
1095  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH)
1096  {
1097  if (rrc == MATCH_ONCE)
1098  {
1099  const pcre_uchar *scode = ecode;
1100  if (*scode != OP_ONCE) /* If not at start, find it */
1101  {
1102  while (*scode == OP_ALT) scode += GET(scode, 1);
1103  scode -= GET(scode, 1);
1104  }
1105  if (md->once_target == scode) rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
1106  }
1107  RRETURN(rrc);
1108  }
1109  ecode += GET(ecode, 1);
1110  md->mark = save_mark;
1111  if (*ecode != OP_ALT) break;
1112  md->capture_last = save_capture_last;
1113  }
1114 
1115  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1116 
1117  /* Handle possessive capturing brackets with an unlimited repeat. We come
1118  here from BRAZERO with allow_zero set TRUE. The offset_vector values are
1119  handled similarly to the normal case above. However, the matching is
1120  different. The end of these brackets will always be OP_KETRPOS, which
1121  returns MATCH_KETRPOS without going further in the pattern. By this means
1122  we can handle the group by iteration rather than recursion, thereby
1123  reducing the amount of stack needed. */
1124 
1125  case OP_CBRAPOS:
1126  case OP_SCBRAPOS:
1127  allow_zero = FALSE;
1128 
1129  POSSESSIVE_CAPTURE:
1130  number = GET2(ecode, 1+LINK_SIZE);
1131  offset = number << 1;
1132 
1133 #ifdef PCRE_DEBUG
1134  printf("start possessive bracket %d\n", number);
1135  printf("subject=");
1136  pchars(eptr, 16, TRUE, md);
1137  printf("\n");
1138 #endif
1139 
1140  if (offset < md->offset_max)
1141  {
1142  matched_once = FALSE;
1143  code_offset = (int)(ecode - md->start_code);
1144 
1145  save_offset1 = md->offset_vector[offset];
1146  save_offset2 = md->offset_vector[offset+1];
1147  save_offset3 = md->offset_vector[md->offset_end - number];
1148  save_capture_last = md->capture_last;
1149 
1150  DPRINTF(("saving %d %d %d\n", save_offset1, save_offset2, save_offset3));
1151 
1152  /* Each time round the loop, save the current subject position for use
1153  when the group matches. For MATCH_MATCH, the group has matched, so we
1154  restart it with a new subject starting position, remembering that we had
1155  at least one match. For MATCH_NOMATCH, carry on with the alternatives, as
1156  usual. If we haven't matched any alternatives in any iteration, check to
1157  see if a previous iteration matched. If so, the group has matched;
1158  continue from afterwards. Otherwise it has failed; restore the previous
1159  capture values before returning NOMATCH. */
1160 
1161  for (;;)
1162  {
1163  md->offset_vector[md->offset_end - number] =
1164  (int)(eptr - md->start_subject);
1165  if (op >= OP_SBRA) md->match_function_type = MATCH_CBEGROUP;
1166  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode], offset_top, md,
1167  eptrb, RM63);
1168  if (rrc == MATCH_KETRPOS)
1169  {
1170  offset_top = md->end_offset_top;
1171  eptr = md->end_match_ptr;
1172  ecode = md->start_code + code_offset;
1173  save_capture_last = md->capture_last;
1174  matched_once = TRUE;
1175  mstart = md->start_match_ptr; /* In case \K changed it */
1176  continue;
1177  }
1178 
1179  /* See comment in the code for capturing groups above about handling
1180  THEN. */
1181 
1182  if (rrc == MATCH_THEN)
1183  {
1184  next = ecode + GET(ecode,1);
1185  if (md->start_match_ptr < next &&
1186  (*ecode == OP_ALT || *next == OP_ALT))
1187  rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
1188  }
1189 
1190  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
1191  md->capture_last = save_capture_last;
1192  ecode += GET(ecode, 1);
1193  if (*ecode != OP_ALT) break;
1194  }
1195 
1196  if (!matched_once)
1197  {
1198  md->offset_vector[offset] = save_offset1;
1199  md->offset_vector[offset+1] = save_offset2;
1200  md->offset_vector[md->offset_end - number] = save_offset3;
1201  }
1202 
1203  if (allow_zero || matched_once)
1204  {
1205  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
1206  break;
1207  }
1208 
1209  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1210  }
1211 
1212  /* FALL THROUGH ... Insufficient room for saving captured contents. Treat
1213  as a non-capturing bracket. */
1214 
1215  /* VVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVV */
1216  /* VVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVV */
1217 
1218  DPRINTF(("insufficient capture room: treat as non-capturing\n"));
1219 
1220  /* VVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVV */
1221  /* VVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVVV */
1222 
1223  /* Non-capturing possessive bracket with unlimited repeat. We come here
1224  from BRAZERO with allow_zero = TRUE. The code is similar to the above,
1225  without the capturing complication. It is written out separately for speed
1226  and cleanliness. */
1227 
1228  case OP_BRAPOS:
1229  case OP_SBRAPOS:
1230  allow_zero = FALSE;
1231 
1232  POSSESSIVE_NON_CAPTURE:
1233  matched_once = FALSE;
1234  code_offset = (int)(ecode - md->start_code);
1235  save_capture_last = md->capture_last;
1236 
1237  for (;;)
1238  {
1239  if (op >= OP_SBRA) md->match_function_type = MATCH_CBEGROUP;
1240  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*ecode], offset_top, md,
1241  eptrb, RM48);
1242  if (rrc == MATCH_KETRPOS)
1243  {
1244  offset_top = md->end_offset_top;
1245  eptr = md->end_match_ptr;
1246  ecode = md->start_code + code_offset;
1247  matched_once = TRUE;
1248  mstart = md->start_match_ptr; /* In case \K reset it */
1249  continue;
1250  }
1251 
1252  /* See comment in the code for capturing groups above about handling
1253  THEN. */
1254 
1255  if (rrc == MATCH_THEN)
1256  {
1257  next = ecode + GET(ecode,1);
1258  if (md->start_match_ptr < next &&
1259  (*ecode == OP_ALT || *next == OP_ALT))
1260  rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
1261  }
1262 
1263  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
1264  ecode += GET(ecode, 1);
1265  if (*ecode != OP_ALT) break;
1266  md->capture_last = save_capture_last;
1267  }
1268 
1269  if (matched_once || allow_zero)
1270  {
1271  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
1272  break;
1273  }
1274  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1275 
1276  /* Control never reaches here. */
1277 
1278  /* Conditional group: compilation checked that there are no more than two
1279  branches. If the condition is false, skipping the first branch takes us
1280  past the end of the item if there is only one branch, but that's exactly
1281  what we want. */
1282 
1283  case OP_COND:
1284  case OP_SCOND:
1285 
1286  /* The variable codelink will be added to ecode when the condition is
1287  false, to get to the second branch. Setting it to the offset to the ALT
1288  or KET, then incrementing ecode achieves this effect. We now have ecode
1289  pointing to the condition or callout. */
1290 
1291  codelink = GET(ecode, 1); /* Offset to the second branch */
1292  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE; /* From this opcode */
1293 
1294  /* Because of the way auto-callout works during compile, a callout item is
1295  inserted between OP_COND and an assertion condition. */
1296 
1297  if (*ecode == OP_CALLOUT)
1298  {
1299  if (PUBL(callout) != NULL)
1300  {
1301  PUBL(callout_block) cb;
1302  cb.version = 2; /* Version 1 of the callout block */
1303  cb.callout_number = ecode[1];
1304  cb.offset_vector = md->offset_vector;
1305 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE8
1306  cb.subject = (PCRE_SPTR)md->start_subject;
1307 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE16
1308  cb.subject = (PCRE_SPTR16)md->start_subject;
1309 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE32
1310  cb.subject = (PCRE_SPTR32)md->start_subject;
1311 #endif
1312  cb.subject_length = (int)(md->end_subject - md->start_subject);
1313  cb.start_match = (int)(mstart - md->start_subject);
1314  cb.current_position = (int)(eptr - md->start_subject);
1315  cb.pattern_position = GET(ecode, 2);
1316  cb.next_item_length = GET(ecode, 2 + LINK_SIZE);
1317  cb.capture_top = offset_top/2;
1318  cb.capture_last = md->capture_last & CAPLMASK;
1319  /* Internal change requires this for API compatibility. */
1320  if (cb.capture_last == 0) cb.capture_last = -1;
1321  cb.callout_data = md->callout_data;
1322  cb.mark = md->nomatch_mark;
1323  if ((rrc = (*PUBL(callout))(&cb)) > 0) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1324  if (rrc < 0) RRETURN(rrc);
1325  }
1326 
1327  /* Advance ecode past the callout, so it now points to the condition. We
1328  must adjust codelink so that the value of ecode+codelink is unchanged. */
1329 
1330  ecode += PRIV(OP_lengths)[OP_CALLOUT];
1331  codelink -= PRIV(OP_lengths)[OP_CALLOUT];
1332  }
1333 
1334  /* Test the various possible conditions */
1335 
1336  condition = FALSE;
1337  switch(condcode = *ecode)
1338  {
1339  case OP_RREF: /* Numbered group recursion test */
1340  if (md->recursive != NULL) /* Not recursing => FALSE */
1341  {
1342  unsigned int recno = GET2(ecode, 1); /* Recursion group number*/
1343  condition = (recno == RREF_ANY || recno == md->recursive->group_num);
1344  }
1345  break;
1346 
1347  case OP_DNRREF: /* Duplicate named group recursion test */
1348  if (md->recursive != NULL)
1349  {
1350  int count = GET2(ecode, 1 + IMM2_SIZE);
1351  pcre_uchar *slot = md->name_table + GET2(ecode, 1) * md->name_entry_size;
1352  while (count-- > 0)
1353  {
1354  unsigned int recno = GET2(slot, 0);
1355  condition = recno == md->recursive->group_num;
1356  if (condition) break;
1357  slot += md->name_entry_size;
1358  }
1359  }
1360  break;
1361 
1362  case OP_CREF: /* Numbered group used test */
1363  offset = GET2(ecode, 1) << 1; /* Doubled ref number */
1364  condition = offset < offset_top && md->offset_vector[offset] >= 0;
1365  break;
1366 
1367  case OP_DNCREF: /* Duplicate named group used test */
1368  {
1369  int count = GET2(ecode, 1 + IMM2_SIZE);
1370  pcre_uchar *slot = md->name_table + GET2(ecode, 1) * md->name_entry_size;
1371  while (count-- > 0)
1372  {
1373  offset = GET2(slot, 0) << 1;
1374  condition = offset < offset_top && md->offset_vector[offset] >= 0;
1375  if (condition) break;
1376  slot += md->name_entry_size;
1377  }
1378  }
1379  break;
1380 
1381  case OP_DEF: /* DEFINE - always false */
1382  break;
1383 
1384  /* The condition is an assertion. Call match() to evaluate it - setting
1385  md->match_function_type to MATCH_CONDASSERT causes it to stop at the end
1386  of an assertion. */
1387 
1388  default:
1389  md->match_function_type = MATCH_CONDASSERT;
1390  RMATCH(eptr, ecode, offset_top, md, NULL, RM3);
1391  if (rrc == MATCH_MATCH)
1392  {
1393  if (md->end_offset_top > offset_top)
1394  offset_top = md->end_offset_top; /* Captures may have happened */
1395  condition = TRUE;
1396 
1397  /* Advance ecode past the assertion to the start of the first branch,
1398  but adjust it so that the general choosing code below works. */
1399 
1400  ecode += GET(ecode, 1);
1401  while (*ecode == OP_ALT) ecode += GET(ecode, 1);
1402  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE - PRIV(OP_lengths)[condcode];
1403  }
1404 
1405  /* PCRE doesn't allow the effect of (*THEN) to escape beyond an
1406  assertion; it is therefore treated as NOMATCH. Any other return is an
1407  error. */
1408 
1409  else if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH && rrc != MATCH_THEN)
1410  {
1411  RRETURN(rrc); /* Need braces because of following else */
1412  }
1413  break;
1414  }
1415 
1416  /* Choose branch according to the condition */
1417 
1418  ecode += condition? PRIV(OP_lengths)[condcode] : codelink;
1419 
1420  /* We are now at the branch that is to be obeyed. As there is only one, we
1421  can use tail recursion to avoid using another stack frame, except when
1422  there is unlimited repeat of a possibly empty group. In the latter case, a
1423  recursive call to match() is always required, unless the second alternative
1424  doesn't exist, in which case we can just plough on. Note that, for
1425  compatibility with Perl, the | in a conditional group is NOT treated as
1426  creating two alternatives. If a THEN is encountered in the branch, it
1427  propagates out to the enclosing alternative (unless nested in a deeper set
1428  of alternatives, of course). */
1429 
1430  if (condition || ecode[-(1+LINK_SIZE)] == OP_ALT)
1431  {
1432  if (op != OP_SCOND)
1433  {
1434  goto TAIL_RECURSE;
1435  }
1436 
1437  md->match_function_type = MATCH_CBEGROUP;
1438  RMATCH(eptr, ecode, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM49);
1439  RRETURN(rrc);
1440  }
1441 
1442  /* Condition false & no alternative; continue after the group. */
1443 
1444  else
1445  {
1446  }
1447  break;
1448 
1449 
1450  /* Before OP_ACCEPT there may be any number of OP_CLOSE opcodes,
1451  to close any currently open capturing brackets. */
1452 
1453  case OP_CLOSE:
1454  number = GET2(ecode, 1); /* Must be less than 65536 */
1455  offset = number << 1;
1456 
1457 #ifdef PCRE_DEBUG
1458  printf("end bracket %d at *ACCEPT", number);
1459  printf("\n");
1460 #endif
1461 
1462  md->capture_last = (md->capture_last & OVFLMASK) | number;
1463  if (offset >= md->offset_max) md->capture_last |= OVFLBIT; else
1464  {
1465  md->offset_vector[offset] =
1466  md->offset_vector[md->offset_end - number];
1467  md->offset_vector[offset+1] = (int)(eptr - md->start_subject);
1468  if (offset_top <= offset) offset_top = offset + 2;
1469  }
1470  ecode += 1 + IMM2_SIZE;
1471  break;
1472 
1473 
1474  /* End of the pattern, either real or forced. */
1475 
1476  case OP_END:
1477  case OP_ACCEPT:
1478  case OP_ASSERT_ACCEPT:
1479 
1480  /* If we have matched an empty string, fail if not in an assertion and not
1481  in a recursion if either PCRE_NOTEMPTY is set, or if PCRE_NOTEMPTY_ATSTART
1482  is set and we have matched at the start of the subject. In both cases,
1483  backtracking will then try other alternatives, if any. */
1484 
1485  if (eptr == mstart && op != OP_ASSERT_ACCEPT &&
1486  md->recursive == NULL &&
1487  (md->notempty ||
1488  (md->notempty_atstart &&
1489  mstart == md->start_subject + md->start_offset)))
1490  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1491 
1492  /* Otherwise, we have a match. */
1493 
1494  md->end_match_ptr = eptr; /* Record where we ended */
1495  md->end_offset_top = offset_top; /* and how many extracts were taken */
1496  md->start_match_ptr = mstart; /* and the start (\K can modify) */
1497 
1498  /* For some reason, the macros don't work properly if an expression is
1499  given as the argument to RRETURN when the heap is in use. */
1500 
1501  rrc = (op == OP_END)? MATCH_MATCH : MATCH_ACCEPT;
1502  RRETURN(rrc);
1503 
1504  /* Assertion brackets. Check the alternative branches in turn - the
1505  matching won't pass the KET for an assertion. If any one branch matches,
1506  the assertion is true. Lookbehind assertions have an OP_REVERSE item at the
1507  start of each branch to move the current point backwards, so the code at
1508  this level is identical to the lookahead case. When the assertion is part
1509  of a condition, we want to return immediately afterwards. The caller of
1510  this incarnation of the match() function will have set MATCH_CONDASSERT in
1511  md->match_function type, and one of these opcodes will be the first opcode
1512  that is processed. We use a local variable that is preserved over calls to
1513  match() to remember this case. */
1514 
1515  case OP_ASSERT:
1516  case OP_ASSERTBACK:
1517  save_mark = md->mark;
1518  if (md->match_function_type == MATCH_CONDASSERT)
1519  {
1520  condassert = TRUE;
1521  md->match_function_type = 0;
1522  }
1523  else condassert = FALSE;
1524 
1525  /* Loop for each branch */
1526 
1527  do
1528  {
1529  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + 1 + LINK_SIZE, offset_top, md, NULL, RM4);
1530 
1531  /* A match means that the assertion is true; break out of the loop
1532  that matches its alternatives. */
1533 
1534  if (rrc == MATCH_MATCH || rrc == MATCH_ACCEPT)
1535  {
1536  mstart = md->start_match_ptr; /* In case \K reset it */
1537  break;
1538  }
1539 
1540  /* If not matched, restore the previous mark setting. */
1541 
1542  md->mark = save_mark;
1543 
1544  /* See comment in the code for capturing groups above about handling
1545  THEN. */
1546 
1547  if (rrc == MATCH_THEN)
1548  {
1549  next = ecode + GET(ecode,1);
1550  if (md->start_match_ptr < next &&
1551  (*ecode == OP_ALT || *next == OP_ALT))
1552  rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
1553  }
1554 
1555  /* Anything other than NOMATCH causes the entire assertion to fail,
1556  passing back the return code. This includes COMMIT, SKIP, PRUNE and an
1557  uncaptured THEN, which means they take their normal effect. This
1558  consistent approach does not always have exactly the same effect as in
1559  Perl. */
1560 
1561  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
1562  ecode += GET(ecode, 1);
1563  }
1564  while (*ecode == OP_ALT); /* Continue for next alternative */
1565 
1566  /* If we have tried all the alternative branches, the assertion has
1567  failed. If not, we broke out after a match. */
1568 
1569  if (*ecode == OP_KET) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1570 
1571  /* If checking an assertion for a condition, return MATCH_MATCH. */
1572 
1573  if (condassert) RRETURN(MATCH_MATCH);
1574 
1575  /* Continue from after a successful assertion, updating the offsets high
1576  water mark, since extracts may have been taken during the assertion. */
1577 
1578  do ecode += GET(ecode,1); while (*ecode == OP_ALT);
1579  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
1580  offset_top = md->end_offset_top;
1581  continue;
1582 
1583  /* Negative assertion: all branches must fail to match for the assertion to
1584  succeed. */
1585 
1586  case OP_ASSERT_NOT:
1587  case OP_ASSERTBACK_NOT:
1588  save_mark = md->mark;
1589  if (md->match_function_type == MATCH_CONDASSERT)
1590  {
1591  condassert = TRUE;
1592  md->match_function_type = 0;
1593  }
1594  else condassert = FALSE;
1595 
1596  /* Loop for each alternative branch. */
1597 
1598  do
1599  {
1600  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + 1 + LINK_SIZE, offset_top, md, NULL, RM5);
1601  md->mark = save_mark; /* Always restore the mark setting */
1602 
1603  switch(rrc)
1604  {
1605  case MATCH_MATCH: /* A successful match means */
1606  case MATCH_ACCEPT: /* the assertion has failed. */
1607  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1608 
1609  case MATCH_NOMATCH: /* Carry on with next branch */
1610  break;
1611 
1612  /* See comment in the code for capturing groups above about handling
1613  THEN. */
1614 
1615  case MATCH_THEN:
1616  next = ecode + GET(ecode,1);
1617  if (md->start_match_ptr < next &&
1618  (*ecode == OP_ALT || *next == OP_ALT))
1619  {
1620  rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
1621  break;
1622  }
1623  /* Otherwise fall through. */
1624 
1625  /* COMMIT, SKIP, PRUNE, and an uncaptured THEN cause the whole
1626  assertion to fail to match, without considering any more alternatives.
1627  Failing to match means the assertion is true. This is a consistent
1628  approach, but does not always have the same effect as in Perl. */
1629 
1630  case MATCH_COMMIT:
1631  case MATCH_SKIP:
1632  case MATCH_SKIP_ARG:
1633  case MATCH_PRUNE:
1634  do ecode += GET(ecode,1); while (*ecode == OP_ALT);
1635  goto NEG_ASSERT_TRUE; /* Break out of alternation loop */
1636 
1637  /* Anything else is an error */
1638 
1639  default:
1640  RRETURN(rrc);
1641  }
1642 
1643  /* Continue with next branch */
1644 
1645  ecode += GET(ecode,1);
1646  }
1647  while (*ecode == OP_ALT);
1648 
1649  /* All branches in the assertion failed to match. */
1650 
1651  NEG_ASSERT_TRUE:
1652  if (condassert) RRETURN(MATCH_MATCH); /* Condition assertion */
1653  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE; /* Continue with current branch */
1654  continue;
1655 
1656  /* Move the subject pointer back. This occurs only at the start of
1657  each branch of a lookbehind assertion. If we are too close to the start to
1658  move back, this match function fails. When working with UTF-8 we move
1659  back a number of characters, not bytes. */
1660 
1661  case OP_REVERSE:
1662 #ifdef SUPPORT_UTF
1663  if (utf)
1664  {
1665  i = GET(ecode, 1);
1666  while (i-- > 0)
1667  {
1668  eptr--;
1669  if (eptr < md->start_subject) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1670  BACKCHAR(eptr);
1671  }
1672  }
1673  else
1674 #endif
1675 
1676  /* No UTF-8 support, or not in UTF-8 mode: count is byte count */
1677 
1678  {
1679  eptr -= GET(ecode, 1);
1680  if (eptr < md->start_subject) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1681  }
1682 
1683  /* Save the earliest consulted character, then skip to next op code */
1684 
1685  if (eptr < md->start_used_ptr) md->start_used_ptr = eptr;
1686  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
1687  break;
1688 
1689  /* The callout item calls an external function, if one is provided, passing
1690  details of the match so far. This is mainly for debugging, though the
1691  function is able to force a failure. */
1692 
1693  case OP_CALLOUT:
1694  if (PUBL(callout) != NULL)
1695  {
1696  PUBL(callout_block) cb;
1697  cb.version = 2; /* Version 1 of the callout block */
1698  cb.callout_number = ecode[1];
1699  cb.offset_vector = md->offset_vector;
1700 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE8
1701  cb.subject = (PCRE_SPTR)md->start_subject;
1702 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE16
1703  cb.subject = (PCRE_SPTR16)md->start_subject;
1704 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE32
1705  cb.subject = (PCRE_SPTR32)md->start_subject;
1706 #endif
1707  cb.subject_length = (int)(md->end_subject - md->start_subject);
1708  cb.start_match = (int)(mstart - md->start_subject);
1709  cb.current_position = (int)(eptr - md->start_subject);
1710  cb.pattern_position = GET(ecode, 2);
1711  cb.next_item_length = GET(ecode, 2 + LINK_SIZE);
1712  cb.capture_top = offset_top/2;
1713  cb.capture_last = md->capture_last & CAPLMASK;
1714  /* Internal change requires this for API compatibility. */
1715  if (cb.capture_last == 0) cb.capture_last = -1;
1716  cb.callout_data = md->callout_data;
1717  cb.mark = md->nomatch_mark;
1718  if ((rrc = (*PUBL(callout))(&cb)) > 0) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1719  if (rrc < 0) RRETURN(rrc);
1720  }
1721  ecode += 2 + 2*LINK_SIZE;
1722  break;
1723 
1724  /* Recursion either matches the current regex, or some subexpression. The
1725  offset data is the offset to the starting bracket from the start of the
1726  whole pattern. (This is so that it works from duplicated subpatterns.)
1727 
1728  The state of the capturing groups is preserved over recursion, and
1729  re-instated afterwards. We don't know how many are started and not yet
1730  finished (offset_top records the completed total) so we just have to save
1731  all the potential data. There may be up to 65535 such values, which is too
1732  large to put on the stack, but using malloc for small numbers seems
1733  expensive. As a compromise, the stack is used when there are no more than
1734  REC_STACK_SAVE_MAX values to store; otherwise malloc is used.
1735 
1736  There are also other values that have to be saved. We use a chained
1737  sequence of blocks that actually live on the stack. Thanks to Robin Houston
1738  for the original version of this logic. It has, however, been hacked around
1739  a lot, so he is not to blame for the current way it works. */
1740 
1741  case OP_RECURSE:
1742  {
1743  recursion_info *ri;
1744  unsigned int recno;
1745 
1746  callpat = md->start_code + GET(ecode, 1);
1747  recno = (callpat == md->start_code)? 0 :
1748  GET2(callpat, 1 + LINK_SIZE);
1749 
1750  /* Check for repeating a recursion without advancing the subject pointer.
1751  This should catch convoluted mutual recursions. (Some simple cases are
1752  caught at compile time.) */
1753 
1754  for (ri = md->recursive; ri != NULL; ri = ri->prevrec)
1755  if (recno == ri->group_num && eptr == ri->subject_position)
1756  RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_RECURSELOOP);
1757 
1758  /* Add to "recursing stack" */
1759 
1760  new_recursive.group_num = recno;
1761  new_recursive.saved_capture_last = md->capture_last;
1762  new_recursive.subject_position = eptr;
1763  new_recursive.prevrec = md->recursive;
1764  md->recursive = &new_recursive;
1765 
1766  /* Where to continue from afterwards */
1767 
1768  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
1769 
1770  /* Now save the offset data */
1771 
1772  new_recursive.saved_max = md->offset_end;
1773  if (new_recursive.saved_max <= REC_STACK_SAVE_MAX)
1774  new_recursive.offset_save = stacksave;
1775  else
1776  {
1777  new_recursive.offset_save =
1778  (int *)(PUBL(malloc))(new_recursive.saved_max * sizeof(int));
1779  if (new_recursive.offset_save == NULL) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_NOMEMORY);
1780  }
1781  memcpy(new_recursive.offset_save, md->offset_vector,
1782  new_recursive.saved_max * sizeof(int));
1783 
1784  /* OK, now we can do the recursion. After processing each alternative,
1785  restore the offset data and the last captured value. If there were nested
1786  recursions, md->recursive might be changed, so reset it before looping.
1787  */
1788 
1789  DPRINTF(("Recursing into group %d\n", new_recursive.group_num));
1790  cbegroup = (*callpat >= OP_SBRA);
1791  do
1792  {
1793  if (cbegroup) md->match_function_type = MATCH_CBEGROUP;
1794  RMATCH(eptr, callpat + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*callpat], offset_top,
1795  md, eptrb, RM6);
1796  memcpy(md->offset_vector, new_recursive.offset_save,
1797  new_recursive.saved_max * sizeof(int));
1798  md->capture_last = new_recursive.saved_capture_last;
1799  md->recursive = new_recursive.prevrec;
1800  if (rrc == MATCH_MATCH || rrc == MATCH_ACCEPT)
1801  {
1802  DPRINTF(("Recursion matched\n"));
1803  if (new_recursive.offset_save != stacksave)
1804  (PUBL(free))(new_recursive.offset_save);
1805 
1806  /* Set where we got to in the subject, and reset the start in case
1807  it was changed by \K. This *is* propagated back out of a recursion,
1808  for Perl compatibility. */
1809 
1810  eptr = md->end_match_ptr;
1811  mstart = md->start_match_ptr;
1812  goto RECURSION_MATCHED; /* Exit loop; end processing */
1813  }
1814 
1815  /* PCRE does not allow THEN, SKIP, PRUNE or COMMIT to escape beyond a
1816  recursion; they cause a NOMATCH for the entire recursion. These codes
1817  are defined in a range that can be tested for. */
1818 
1819  if (rrc >= MATCH_BACKTRACK_MIN && rrc <= MATCH_BACKTRACK_MAX)
1820  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1821 
1822  /* Any return code other than NOMATCH is an error. */
1823 
1824  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH)
1825  {
1826  DPRINTF(("Recursion gave error %d\n", rrc));
1827  if (new_recursive.offset_save != stacksave)
1828  (PUBL(free))(new_recursive.offset_save);
1829  RRETURN(rrc);
1830  }
1831 
1832  md->recursive = &new_recursive;
1833  callpat += GET(callpat, 1);
1834  }
1835  while (*callpat == OP_ALT);
1836 
1837  DPRINTF(("Recursion didn't match\n"));
1838  md->recursive = new_recursive.prevrec;
1839  if (new_recursive.offset_save != stacksave)
1840  (PUBL(free))(new_recursive.offset_save);
1841  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
1842  }
1843 
1844  RECURSION_MATCHED:
1845  break;
1846 
1847  /* An alternation is the end of a branch; scan along to find the end of the
1848  bracketed group and go to there. */
1849 
1850  case OP_ALT:
1851  do ecode += GET(ecode,1); while (*ecode == OP_ALT);
1852  break;
1853 
1854  /* BRAZERO, BRAMINZERO and SKIPZERO occur just before a bracket group,
1855  indicating that it may occur zero times. It may repeat infinitely, or not
1856  at all - i.e. it could be ()* or ()? or even (){0} in the pattern. Brackets
1857  with fixed upper repeat limits are compiled as a number of copies, with the
1858  optional ones preceded by BRAZERO or BRAMINZERO. */
1859 
1860  case OP_BRAZERO:
1861  next = ecode + 1;
1862  RMATCH(eptr, next, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM10);
1863  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
1864  do next += GET(next, 1); while (*next == OP_ALT);
1865  ecode = next + 1 + LINK_SIZE;
1866  break;
1867 
1868  case OP_BRAMINZERO:
1869  next = ecode + 1;
1870  do next += GET(next, 1); while (*next == OP_ALT);
1871  RMATCH(eptr, next + 1+LINK_SIZE, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM11);
1872  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
1873  ecode++;
1874  break;
1875 
1876  case OP_SKIPZERO:
1877  next = ecode+1;
1878  do next += GET(next,1); while (*next == OP_ALT);
1879  ecode = next + 1 + LINK_SIZE;
1880  break;
1881 
1882  /* BRAPOSZERO occurs before a possessive bracket group. Don't do anything
1883  here; just jump to the group, with allow_zero set TRUE. */
1884 
1885  case OP_BRAPOSZERO:
1886  op = *(++ecode);
1887  allow_zero = TRUE;
1888  if (op == OP_CBRAPOS || op == OP_SCBRAPOS) goto POSSESSIVE_CAPTURE;
1889  goto POSSESSIVE_NON_CAPTURE;
1890 
1891  /* End of a group, repeated or non-repeating. */
1892 
1893  case OP_KET:
1894  case OP_KETRMIN:
1895  case OP_KETRMAX:
1896  case OP_KETRPOS:
1897  prev = ecode - GET(ecode, 1);
1898 
1899  /* If this was a group that remembered the subject start, in order to break
1900  infinite repeats of empty string matches, retrieve the subject start from
1901  the chain. Otherwise, set it NULL. */
1902 
1903  if (*prev >= OP_SBRA || *prev == OP_ONCE)
1904  {
1905  saved_eptr = eptrb->epb_saved_eptr; /* Value at start of group */
1906  eptrb = eptrb->epb_prev; /* Backup to previous group */
1907  }
1908  else saved_eptr = NULL;
1909 
1910  /* If we are at the end of an assertion group or a non-capturing atomic
1911  group, stop matching and return MATCH_MATCH, but record the current high
1912  water mark for use by positive assertions. We also need to record the match
1913  start in case it was changed by \K. */
1914 
1915  if ((*prev >= OP_ASSERT && *prev <= OP_ASSERTBACK_NOT) ||
1916  *prev == OP_ONCE_NC)
1917  {
1918  md->end_match_ptr = eptr; /* For ONCE_NC */
1919  md->end_offset_top = offset_top;
1920  md->start_match_ptr = mstart;
1921  RRETURN(MATCH_MATCH); /* Sets md->mark */
1922  }
1923 
1924  /* For capturing groups we have to check the group number back at the start
1925  and if necessary complete handling an extraction by setting the offsets and
1926  bumping the high water mark. Whole-pattern recursion is coded as a recurse
1927  into group 0, so it won't be picked up here. Instead, we catch it when the
1928  OP_END is reached. Other recursion is handled here. We just have to record
1929  the current subject position and start match pointer and give a MATCH
1930  return. */
1931 
1932  if (*prev == OP_CBRA || *prev == OP_SCBRA ||
1933  *prev == OP_CBRAPOS || *prev == OP_SCBRAPOS)
1934  {
1935  number = GET2(prev, 1+LINK_SIZE);
1936  offset = number << 1;
1937 
1938 #ifdef PCRE_DEBUG
1939  printf("end bracket %d", number);
1940  printf("\n");
1941 #endif
1942 
1943  /* Handle a recursively called group. */
1944 
1945  if (md->recursive != NULL && md->recursive->group_num == number)
1946  {
1947  md->end_match_ptr = eptr;
1948  md->start_match_ptr = mstart;
1949  RRETURN(MATCH_MATCH);
1950  }
1951 
1952  /* Deal with capturing */
1953 
1954  md->capture_last = (md->capture_last & OVFLMASK) | number;
1955  if (offset >= md->offset_max) md->capture_last |= OVFLBIT; else
1956  {
1957  /* If offset is greater than offset_top, it means that we are
1958  "skipping" a capturing group, and that group's offsets must be marked
1959  unset. In earlier versions of PCRE, all the offsets were unset at the
1960  start of matching, but this doesn't work because atomic groups and
1961  assertions can cause a value to be set that should later be unset.
1962  Example: matching /(?>(a))b|(a)c/ against "ac". This sets group 1 as
1963  part of the atomic group, but this is not on the final matching path,
1964  so must be unset when 2 is set. (If there is no group 2, there is no
1965  problem, because offset_top will then be 2, indicating no capture.) */
1966 
1967  if (offset > offset_top)
1968  {
1969  register int *iptr = md->offset_vector + offset_top;
1970  register int *iend = md->offset_vector + offset;
1971  while (iptr < iend) *iptr++ = -1;
1972  }
1973 
1974  /* Now make the extraction */
1975 
1976  md->offset_vector[offset] =
1977  md->offset_vector[md->offset_end - number];
1978  md->offset_vector[offset+1] = (int)(eptr - md->start_subject);
1979  if (offset_top <= offset) offset_top = offset + 2;
1980  }
1981  }
1982 
1983  /* For an ordinary non-repeating ket, just continue at this level. This
1984  also happens for a repeating ket if no characters were matched in the
1985  group. This is the forcible breaking of infinite loops as implemented in
1986  Perl 5.005. For a non-repeating atomic group that includes captures,
1987  establish a backup point by processing the rest of the pattern at a lower
1988  level. If this results in a NOMATCH return, pass MATCH_ONCE back to the
1989  original OP_ONCE level, thereby bypassing intermediate backup points, but
1990  resetting any captures that happened along the way. */
1991 
1992  if (*ecode == OP_KET || eptr == saved_eptr)
1993  {
1994  if (*prev == OP_ONCE)
1995  {
1996  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + 1 + LINK_SIZE, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM12);
1997  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
1998  md->once_target = prev; /* Level at which to change to MATCH_NOMATCH */
1999  RRETURN(MATCH_ONCE);
2000  }
2001  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE; /* Carry on at this level */
2002  break;
2003  }
2004 
2005  /* OP_KETRPOS is a possessive repeating ket. Remember the current position,
2006  and return the MATCH_KETRPOS. This makes it possible to do the repeats one
2007  at a time from the outer level, thus saving stack. */
2008 
2009  if (*ecode == OP_KETRPOS)
2010  {
2011  md->start_match_ptr = mstart; /* In case \K reset it */
2012  md->end_match_ptr = eptr;
2013  md->end_offset_top = offset_top;
2014  RRETURN(MATCH_KETRPOS);
2015  }
2016 
2017  /* The normal repeating kets try the rest of the pattern or restart from
2018  the preceding bracket, in the appropriate order. In the second case, we can
2019  use tail recursion to avoid using another stack frame, unless we have an
2020  an atomic group or an unlimited repeat of a group that can match an empty
2021  string. */
2022 
2023  if (*ecode == OP_KETRMIN)
2024  {
2025  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + 1 + LINK_SIZE, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM7);
2026  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
2027  if (*prev == OP_ONCE)
2028  {
2029  RMATCH(eptr, prev, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM8);
2030  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
2031  md->once_target = prev; /* Level at which to change to MATCH_NOMATCH */
2032  RRETURN(MATCH_ONCE);
2033  }
2034  if (*prev >= OP_SBRA) /* Could match an empty string */
2035  {
2036  RMATCH(eptr, prev, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM50);
2037  RRETURN(rrc);
2038  }
2039  ecode = prev;
2040  goto TAIL_RECURSE;
2041  }
2042  else /* OP_KETRMAX */
2043  {
2044  RMATCH(eptr, prev, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM13);
2045  if (rrc == MATCH_ONCE && md->once_target == prev) rrc = MATCH_NOMATCH;
2046  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
2047  if (*prev == OP_ONCE)
2048  {
2049  RMATCH(eptr, ecode + 1 + LINK_SIZE, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM9);
2050  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
2051  md->once_target = prev;
2052  RRETURN(MATCH_ONCE);
2053  }
2054  ecode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
2055  goto TAIL_RECURSE;
2056  }
2057  /* Control never gets here */
2058 
2059  /* Not multiline mode: start of subject assertion, unless notbol. */
2060 
2061  case OP_CIRC:
2062  if (md->notbol && eptr == md->start_subject) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2063 
2064  /* Start of subject assertion */
2065 
2066  case OP_SOD:
2067  if (eptr != md->start_subject) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2068  ecode++;
2069  break;
2070 
2071  /* Multiline mode: start of subject unless notbol, or after any newline. */
2072 
2073  case OP_CIRCM:
2074  if (md->notbol && eptr == md->start_subject) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2075  if (eptr != md->start_subject &&
2076  (eptr == md->end_subject || !WAS_NEWLINE(eptr)))
2077  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2078  ecode++;
2079  break;
2080 
2081  /* Start of match assertion */
2082 
2083  case OP_SOM:
2084  if (eptr != md->start_subject + md->start_offset) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2085  ecode++;
2086  break;
2087 
2088  /* Reset the start of match point */
2089 
2090  case OP_SET_SOM:
2091  mstart = eptr;
2092  ecode++;
2093  break;
2094 
2095  /* Multiline mode: assert before any newline, or before end of subject
2096  unless noteol is set. */
2097 
2098  case OP_DOLLM:
2099  if (eptr < md->end_subject)
2100  {
2101  if (!IS_NEWLINE(eptr))
2102  {
2103  if (md->partial != 0 &&
2104  eptr + 1 >= md->end_subject &&
2105  NLBLOCK->nltype == NLTYPE_FIXED &&
2106  NLBLOCK->nllen == 2 &&
2107  UCHAR21TEST(eptr) == NLBLOCK->nl[0])
2108  {
2109  md->hitend = TRUE;
2110  if (md->partial > 1) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_PARTIAL);
2111  }
2112  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2113  }
2114  }
2115  else
2116  {
2117  if (md->noteol) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2118  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2119  }
2120  ecode++;
2121  break;
2122 
2123  /* Not multiline mode: assert before a terminating newline or before end of
2124  subject unless noteol is set. */
2125 
2126  case OP_DOLL:
2127  if (md->noteol) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2128  if (!md->endonly) goto ASSERT_NL_OR_EOS;
2129 
2130  /* ... else fall through for endonly */
2131 
2132  /* End of subject assertion (\z) */
2133 
2134  case OP_EOD:
2135  if (eptr < md->end_subject) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2136  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2137  ecode++;
2138  break;
2139 
2140  /* End of subject or ending \n assertion (\Z) */
2141 
2142  case OP_EODN:
2143  ASSERT_NL_OR_EOS:
2144  if (eptr < md->end_subject &&
2145  (!IS_NEWLINE(eptr) || eptr != md->end_subject - md->nllen))
2146  {
2147  if (md->partial != 0 &&
2148  eptr + 1 >= md->end_subject &&
2149  NLBLOCK->nltype == NLTYPE_FIXED &&
2150  NLBLOCK->nllen == 2 &&
2151  UCHAR21TEST(eptr) == NLBLOCK->nl[0])
2152  {
2153  md->hitend = TRUE;
2154  if (md->partial > 1) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_PARTIAL);
2155  }
2156  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2157  }
2158 
2159  /* Either at end of string or \n before end. */
2160 
2161  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2162  ecode++;
2163  break;
2164 
2165  /* Word boundary assertions */
2166 
2167  case OP_NOT_WORD_BOUNDARY:
2168  case OP_WORD_BOUNDARY:
2169  {
2170 
2171  /* Find out if the previous and current characters are "word" characters.
2172  It takes a bit more work in UTF-8 mode. Characters > 255 are assumed to
2173  be "non-word" characters. Remember the earliest consulted character for
2174  partial matching. */
2175 
2176 #ifdef SUPPORT_UTF
2177  if (utf)
2178  {
2179  /* Get status of previous character */
2180 
2181  if (eptr == md->start_subject) prev_is_word = FALSE; else
2182  {
2183  PCRE_PUCHAR lastptr = eptr - 1;
2184  BACKCHAR(lastptr);
2185  if (lastptr < md->start_used_ptr) md->start_used_ptr = lastptr;
2186  GETCHAR(c, lastptr);
2187 #ifdef SUPPORT_UCP
2188  if (md->use_ucp)
2189  {
2190  if (c == '_') prev_is_word = TRUE; else
2191  {
2192  int cat = UCD_CATEGORY(c);
2193  prev_is_word = (cat == ucp_L || cat == ucp_N);
2194  }
2195  }
2196  else
2197 #endif
2198  prev_is_word = c < 256 && (md->ctypes[c] & ctype_word) != 0;
2199  }
2200 
2201  /* Get status of next character */
2202 
2203  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
2204  {
2205  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2206  cur_is_word = FALSE;
2207  }
2208  else
2209  {
2210  GETCHAR(c, eptr);
2211 #ifdef SUPPORT_UCP
2212  if (md->use_ucp)
2213  {
2214  if (c == '_') cur_is_word = TRUE; else
2215  {
2216  int cat = UCD_CATEGORY(c);
2217  cur_is_word = (cat == ucp_L || cat == ucp_N);
2218  }
2219  }
2220  else
2221 #endif
2222  cur_is_word = c < 256 && (md->ctypes[c] & ctype_word) != 0;
2223  }
2224  }
2225  else
2226 #endif
2227 
2228  /* Not in UTF-8 mode, but we may still have PCRE_UCP set, and for
2229  consistency with the behaviour of \w we do use it in this case. */
2230 
2231  {
2232  /* Get status of previous character */
2233 
2234  if (eptr == md->start_subject) prev_is_word = FALSE; else
2235  {
2236  if (eptr <= md->start_used_ptr) md->start_used_ptr = eptr - 1;
2237 #ifdef SUPPORT_UCP
2238  if (md->use_ucp)
2239  {
2240  c = eptr[-1];
2241  if (c == '_') prev_is_word = TRUE; else
2242  {
2243  int cat = UCD_CATEGORY(c);
2244  prev_is_word = (cat == ucp_L || cat == ucp_N);
2245  }
2246  }
2247  else
2248 #endif
2249  prev_is_word = MAX_255(eptr[-1])
2250  && ((md->ctypes[eptr[-1]] & ctype_word) != 0);
2251  }
2252 
2253  /* Get status of next character */
2254 
2255  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
2256  {
2257  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2258  cur_is_word = FALSE;
2259  }
2260  else
2261 #ifdef SUPPORT_UCP
2262  if (md->use_ucp)
2263  {
2264  c = *eptr;
2265  if (c == '_') cur_is_word = TRUE; else
2266  {
2267  int cat = UCD_CATEGORY(c);
2268  cur_is_word = (cat == ucp_L || cat == ucp_N);
2269  }
2270  }
2271  else
2272 #endif
2273  cur_is_word = MAX_255(*eptr)
2274  && ((md->ctypes[*eptr] & ctype_word) != 0);
2275  }
2276 
2277  /* Now see if the situation is what we want */
2278 
2279  if ((*ecode++ == OP_WORD_BOUNDARY)?
2280  cur_is_word == prev_is_word : cur_is_word != prev_is_word)
2281  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2282  }
2283  break;
2284 
2285  /* Match any single character type except newline; have to take care with
2286  CRLF newlines and partial matching. */
2287 
2288  case OP_ANY:
2289  if (IS_NEWLINE(eptr)) RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2290  if (md->partial != 0 &&
2291  eptr + 1 >= md->end_subject &&
2292  NLBLOCK->nltype == NLTYPE_FIXED &&
2293  NLBLOCK->nllen == 2 &&
2294  UCHAR21TEST(eptr) == NLBLOCK->nl[0])
2295  {
2296  md->hitend = TRUE;
2297  if (md->partial > 1) RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_PARTIAL);
2298  }
2299 
2300  /* Fall through */
2301 
2302  /* Match any single character whatsoever. */
2303 
2304  case OP_ALLANY:
2305  if (eptr >= md->end_subject) /* DO NOT merge the eptr++ here; it must */
2306  { /* not be updated before SCHECK_PARTIAL. */
2307  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2308  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2309  }
2310  eptr++;
2311 #ifdef SUPPORT_UTF
2312  if (utf) ACROSSCHAR(eptr < md->end_subject, *eptr, eptr++);
2313 #endif
2314  ecode++;

2316 
2317  /* Match a single byte, even in UTF-8 mode. This opcode really does match
2318  any byte, even newline, independent of the setting of PCRE_DOTALL. */
2319 
2320  case OP_ANYBYTE:
2321  if (eptr >= md->end_subject) /* DO NOT merge the eptr++ here; it must */
2322  { /* not be updated before SCHECK_PARTIAL. */
2323  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2324  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2325  }
2326  eptr++;
2327  ecode++;
2328  break;
2329 
2330  case OP_NOT_DIGIT:
2331  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
2332  {
2333  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2334  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2335  }
2336  GETCHARINCTEST(c, eptr);
2337  if (
2338 #if defined SUPPORT_UTF || !(defined COMPILE_PCRE8)
2339  c < 256 &&
2340 #endif
2341  (md->ctypes[c] & ctype_digit) != 0
2342  )
2343  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2344  ecode++;
2345  break;
2346 
2347  case OP_DIGIT:
2348  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
2349  {
2350  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
2351  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2352  }
2353  GETCHARINCTEST(c, eptr);
2354  if (
2355 #if defined SUPPORT_UTF || !(defined COMPILE_PCRE8)
2356  c > 255 ||
2357 #endif
2358  (md->ctypes[c] & ctype_digit) == 0
2359  )
2360  RRETURN(MATCH_NOMATCH);
2361  ecode++;

2363

2369  }
2370  GETCHARINCTEST(c, eptr);

4604  }

5982  eptr = md->end_subject;
5983  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
5984  }
5985  else eptr += c;
5986  break;
5987 
5988  case OP_ANYNL:
5989  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
5990  {
5991  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
5992  {
5993  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
5994  break;
5995  }
5996  c = *eptr;
5997  if (c == CHAR_CR)
5998  {
5999  if (++eptr >= md->end_subject) break;
6000  if (*eptr == CHAR_LF) eptr++;
6001  }
6002  else
6003  {
6004  if (c != CHAR_LF && (md->bsr_anycrlf ||
6005  (c != CHAR_VT && c != CHAR_FF && c != CHAR_NEL
6006 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE16 || defined COMPILE_PCRE32
6007  && c != 0x2028 && c != 0x2029
6008 #endif
6009  ))) break;
6010  eptr++;
6011  }
6012  }
6013  break;
6014 
6015  case OP_NOT_HSPACE:
6016  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6017  {
6018  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6019  {
6020  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6021  break;
6022  }
6023  switch(*eptr)
6024  {
6025  default: eptr++; break;
6026  HSPACE_BYTE_CASES:
6027 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE16 || defined COMPILE_PCRE32
6028  HSPACE_MULTIBYTE_CASES:
6029 #endif
6030  goto ENDLOOP00;
6031  }
6032  }
6033  ENDLOOP00:
6034  break;
6035 
6036  case OP_HSPACE:
6037  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6038  {
6039  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6040  {
6041  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6042  break;
6043  }
6044  switch(*eptr)
6045  {
6046  default: goto ENDLOOP01;
6047  HSPACE_BYTE_CASES:
6048 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE16 || defined COMPILE_PCRE32
6049  HSPACE_MULTIBYTE_CASES:
6050 #endif
6051  eptr++; break;
6052  }
6053  }
6054  ENDLOOP01:
6055  break;
6056 
6057  case OP_NOT_VSPACE:
6058  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6059  {
6060  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6061  {
6062  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6063  break;
6064  }
6065  switch(*eptr)
6066  {
6067  default: eptr++; break;
6068  VSPACE_BYTE_CASES:
6069 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE16 || defined COMPILE_PCRE32
6070  VSPACE_MULTIBYTE_CASES:
6071 #endif
6072  goto ENDLOOP02;
6073  }
6074  }
6075  ENDLOOP02:
6076  break;
6077 
6078  case OP_VSPACE:
6079  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6080  {
6081  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6082  {
6083  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6084  break;
6085  }
6086  switch(*eptr)
6087  {
6088  default: goto ENDLOOP03;
6089  VSPACE_BYTE_CASES:
6090 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE16 || defined COMPILE_PCRE32
6091  VSPACE_MULTIBYTE_CASES:
6092 #endif
6093  eptr++; break;
6094  }
6095  }
6096  ENDLOOP03:
6097  break;
6098 
6099  case OP_NOT_DIGIT:
6100  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6101  {
6102  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6103  {
6104  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6105  break;
6106  }
6107  if (MAX_255(*eptr) && (md->ctypes[*eptr] & ctype_digit) != 0) break;
6108  eptr++;
6109  }
6110  break;
6111 
6112  case OP_DIGIT:
6113  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6114  {
6115  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6116  {
6117  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6118  break;
6119  }
6120  if (!MAX_255(*eptr) || (md->ctypes[*eptr] & ctype_digit) == 0) break;
6121  eptr++;
6122  }
6123  break;
6124 
6125  case OP_NOT_WHITESPACE:
6126  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6127  {
6128  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6129  {
6130  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6131  break;
6132  }
6133  if (MAX_255(*eptr) && (md->ctypes[*eptr] & ctype_space) != 0) break;
6134  eptr++;
6135  }
6136  break;
6137 
6138  case OP_WHITESPACE:
6139  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6140  {
6141  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6142  {
6143  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6144  break;
6145  }
6146  if (!MAX_255(*eptr) || (md->ctypes[*eptr] & ctype_space) == 0) break;
6147  eptr++;
6148  }
6149  break;
6150 
6151  case OP_NOT_WORDCHAR:
6152  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6153  {
6154  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6155  {
6156  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6157  break;
6158  }
6159  if (MAX_255(*eptr) && (md->ctypes[*eptr] & ctype_word) != 0) break;
6160  eptr++;
6161  }
6162  break;
6163 
6164  case OP_WORDCHAR:
6165  for (i = min; i < max; i++)
6166  {
6167  if (eptr >= md->end_subject)
6168  {
6169  SCHECK_PARTIAL();
6170  break;
6171  }
6172  if (!MAX_255(*eptr) || (md->ctypes[*eptr] & ctype_word) == 0) break;
6173  eptr++;
6174  }
6175  break;
6176 
6177  default:
6178  RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_INTERNAL);
6179  }
6180 
6181  if (possessive) continue; /* No backtracking */
6182  for (;;)
6183  {
6184  if (eptr == pp) goto TAIL_RECURSE;
6185  RMATCH(eptr, ecode, offset_top, md, eptrb, RM47);
6186  if (rrc != MATCH_NOMATCH) RRETURN(rrc);
6187  eptr--;
6188  if (ctype == OP_ANYNL && eptr > pp && *eptr == CHAR_LF &&
6189  eptr[-1] == CHAR_CR) eptr--;
6190  }
6191  }
6192 
6193  /* Control never gets here */
6194  }
6195 
6196  /* There's been some horrible disaster. Arrival here can only mean there is
6197  something seriously wrong in the code above or the OP_xxx definitions. */
6198 
6199  default:
6200  DPRINTF(("Unknown opcode %d\n", *ecode));
6201  RRETURN(PCRE_ERROR_UNKNOWN_OPCODE);
6202  }
6203 
6204  /* Do not stick any code in here without much thought; it is assumed
6205  that "continue" in the code above comes out to here to repeat the main
6206  loop. */
6207 
6208  } /* End of main loop */
6209 /* Control never reaches here */

6216 #ifdef NO_RECURSE

6328 /*************************************************
6329 * Execute a Regular Expression *
6330 *************************************************/
6331 
6332 /* This function applies a compiled re to a subject string and picks out
6333 portions of the string if it matches. Two elements in the vector are set for
6334 each substring: the offsets to the start and end of the substring.
6335 
6336 Arguments:
6337  argument_re points to the compiled expression
6338  extra_data points to extra data or is NULL
6339  subject points to the subject string
6340  length length of subject string (may contain binary zeros)
6341  start_offset where to start in the subject string
6342  options option bits
6343  offsets points to a vector of ints to be filled in with offsets
6344  offsetcount the number of elements in the vector
6345 
6346 Returns: > 0 => success; value is the number of elements filled in
6347  = 0 => success, but offsets is not big enough
6348  -1 => failed to match
6349  < -1 => some kind of unexpected problem
6350 */
6351 
6352 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE8
6353 PCRE_EXP_DEFN int PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
6354 pcre_exec(const pcre *argument_re, const pcre_extra *extra_data,
6355  PCRE_SPTR subject, int length, int start_offset, int options, int *offsets,
6356  int offsetcount)

6358 PCRE_EXP_DEFN int PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
6359 pcre16_exec(const pcre16 *argument_re, const pcre16_extra *extra_data,
6360  PCRE_SPTR16 subject, int length, int start_offset, int options, int *offsets,
6361  int offsetcount)
6362 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE32
6363 PCRE_EXP_DEFN int PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
6364 pcre32_exec(const pcre32 *argument_re, const pcre32_extra *extra_data,
6365  PCRE_SPTR32 subject, int length, int start_offset, int options, int *offsets,
6366  int offsetcount)
6367 #endif

6370 int newline;

6372 BOOL anchored;
6373 BOOL startline;
6374 BOOL firstline;
6375 BOOL utf;

6377 BOOL has_req_char = FALSE;
6378 pcre_uchar first_char = 0;
6379 pcre_uchar first_char2 = 0;
6380 pcre_uchar req_char = 0;
6381 pcre_uchar req_char2 = 0;

6387 PCRE_PUCHAR end_subject;

6393 const REAL_PCRE *re = (const REAL_PCRE *)argument_re;
6394 
6395 #ifdef NO_RECURSE
6396 heapframe frame_zero;
6397 frame_zero.Xprevframe = NULL; /* Marks the top level */
6398 frame_zero.Xnextframe = NULL; /* None are allocated yet */
6399 md->match_frames_base = &frame_zero;
6400 #endif
6401 
6402 /* Check for the special magic call that measures the size of the stack used
6403 per recursive call of match(). Without the funny casting for sizeof, a Windows
6404 compiler gave this error: "unary minus operator applied to unsigned type,
6405 result still unsigned". Hopefully the cast fixes that. */
6406 
6407 if (re == NULL && extra_data == NULL && subject == NULL && length == -999 &&
6408  start_offset == -999)
6409 #ifdef NO_RECURSE
6410  return -((int)sizeof(heapframe));
6411 #else
6412  return match(NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, 0);
6413 #endif
6414 
6415 /* Plausibility checks */
6416 
6417 if ((options & ~PUBLIC_EXEC_OPTIONS) != 0) return PCRE_ERROR_BADOPTION;
6418 if (re == NULL || subject == NULL || (offsets == NULL && offsetcount > 0))
6419  return PCRE_ERROR_NULL;
6420 if (offsetcount < 0) return PCRE_ERROR_BADCOUNT;
6421 if (length < 0) return PCRE_ERROR_BADLENGTH;
6422 if (start_offset < 0 || start_offset > length) return PCRE_ERROR_BADOFFSET;
6423 
6424 /* Check that the first field in the block is the magic number. If it is not,
6425 return with PCRE_ERROR_BADMAGIC. However, if the magic number is equal to
6426 REVERSED_MAGIC_NUMBER we return with PCRE_ERROR_BADENDIANNESS, which
6427 means that the pattern is likely compiled with different endianness. */
6428 
6429 if (re->magic_number != MAGIC_NUMBER)
6430  return re->magic_number == REVERSED_MAGIC_NUMBER?
6431  PCRE_ERROR_BADENDIANNESS:PCRE_ERROR_BADMAGIC;
6432 if ((re->flags & PCRE_MODE) == 0) return PCRE_ERROR_BADMODE;
6433 
6434 /* These two settings are used in the code for checking a UTF-8 string that
6435 follows immediately afterwards. Other values in the md block are used only
6436 during "normal" pcre_exec() processing, not when the JIT support is in use,
6437 so they are set up later. */

6439 /* PCRE_UTF16 has the same value as PCRE_UTF8. */
6440 utf = md->utf = (re->options & PCRE_UTF8) != 0;
6441 md->partial = ((options & PCRE_PARTIAL_HARD) != 0)? 2 :
6442  ((options & PCRE_PARTIAL_SOFT) != 0)? 1 : 0;

6446

6449  {

6452  if (errorcode != 0)
6453  {
6454  if (offsetcount >= 2)

6456  offsets[0] = erroroffset;
6457  offsets[1] = errorcode;

6461  PCRE_ERROR_SHORTUTF8 : PCRE_ERROR_BADUTF8;
6462 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE16
6463  return (errorcode <= PCRE_UTF16_ERR1 && md->partial > 1)?
6464  PCRE_ERROR_SHORTUTF16 : PCRE_ERROR_BADUTF16;
6465 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE32
6466  return PCRE_ERROR_BADUTF32;
6467 #endif

6473  return PCRE_ERROR_BADUTF8_OFFSET;

6479 executable instead of the rest of this function. Most options must be set at

6481 an unsupported flag is set. */

6484 if (extra_data != NULL
6485  && (extra_data->flags & (PCRE_EXTRA_EXECUTABLE_JIT |
6486  PCRE_EXTRA_TABLES)) == PCRE_EXTRA_EXECUTABLE_JIT

6492

6494  mode is not compiled. In this case we simply fallback to interpreter. */

6501 numbers associated with a given name, for condition testing. */
6502 
6503 md->name_table = (pcre_uchar *)re + re->name_table_offset;
6504 md->name_count = re->name_count;
6505 md->name_entry_size = re->name_entry_size;

6512 md->match_limit_recursion = MATCH_LIMIT_RECURSION;

6526  if ((flags & PCRE_EXTRA_MATCH_LIMIT) != 0)
